Burkina Faso Social Norms Research transcripts

Ramoudane Orou Sannou

01/10/2020

Introduction

This is a summary text analysis of interview and focus group transcripts from the study on social norms related to the registration of births, marriages, and deaths conducted at the HDSS sites of Kaya, Nanoro, and Nouna in Burkina Faso. The analysis provides a typology of the interviewees and reports on the general insights that emerge from the responses given.

Word cloud : most frequent words

“Marriage” , “Naissances” and “Femme” are the most commonly used words. Let’s see in what context those words are used by looking at the text that follows the use of each word.

Clearly, in nearly 90% of cases the word “femme” (woman) is followed by the verb “accoucher” (to give birth), revealing that women often associate themsevelves with the act of giving birth and not the registration of the new-born. However, one of the sentences containing the word “femme” refers to women “who leave their marital home without informing their husband” and probably refers to the risks associated with marriage registration and the reasons for men’s reluctance to do it.

In many cases, the word “birth” is used by women to indicate the importance of having a birth certificate. The importance is linked to having an identity and being able to send children to school. They also mentionned the slowness in establishing birth certificates which would be a blocking factor.

Men seem to refer to the word “naissance” to evoke the important information contained in the birth certificate. They also talk about the difficulty of giving all the information about the new-born systematically after birth. For example, in Muslim families, the child’s first name is known after 7 days.

The texts following the word ‘’marriage’’ are rather ambiguous. Some people think that marriage registration depends on the goals the couple has set for themselves, others allude to the fact that it is difficult to end a registered marriage.
